                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d727">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77/2615b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Warren</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-07-17T15:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 17, 1922—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>73. Please bring informally to the attention of the Foreign Office the following
                    draft of a confidential memorandum to the Powers concerned relating to the
                    Chinese Eastern Railway and say that in view of the original agreement having
                    been made primarily by Japan and the United States I should be glad to have
                    their comments on the action proposed. A similar preliminary inquiry is being
                    made of the British Government.</p>
                <p>[Here follows draft identical with that in telegram number 209 of the same date
                    to the Ambassador in Great Britain, printed <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi>]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
